edu.jsu.mcis

Class Arg

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.jsu.mcis.Arg

  • public class Arg
extends java.lang.Object
    Holds information about the argument.
    An argument can be either positional or named.
    There is an option to make both types of arguments restricted.
    Named arguments can be required.

    Positional arguments are required. These arguments will be core to the program.
    An example of a positional argument would be length, width and height in a volume calculating program.

    Named arguments are considered named.
    An example of a named argument would be numeric precision in a volume calculating program.
    The default precision could be to two decimal places, but have support for more.

    Restricted arguments are limited to a specified set of values. This can be thought of as an enumeration.
    An example of a restricted (named) argument would be the shape of an object in a volume calculating program.
    It could be limited to the following list: box, sphere, or a cylinder.

    Required arguments are named arguments that have been declared necessary for the program to function.
    If a required named argument is not used then an error will be thrown. An example would be the shape of an object in a volume calculating program.
